The Oath-Crossing is the neutral glade in the Great Northern Forest's Northern Crown where Midgaard and Kowloon formalized charter coexistence.
It marks the moment when two expanding city-states with overlapping territorial claims chose negotiated boundary over armed contest.
The glade was selected as the meeting site because it was equidistant from both cities' northern patrol boundaries at the time and had no prior territorial claim by either.
The agreement signed at the Oath-Crossing established the Great Northern Forest as a shared-jurisdiction zone rather than a contested border territory.
The terms set mutual recognition of each city's existing route certifications, defined a joint arbitration process for new claims, and created a witness requirement for all future territorial agreements in the Forest zone.
The crossing site was marked with two boundary stones — one bearing Midgaard's charter seal, one bearing the Neon Covenant's mark — placed side by side rather than facing each other.
The placement was deliberate: the stones do not mark a border between two territories; they mark a shared commitment to a single process.
The Oath-Crossing is the foundational document for the Great Northern Forest's current governance framework, which treats the Forest as a managed shared resource rather than a divided territory.
Neither city fully honors the original terms in current practice: Midgaard extends charter registration into Forest zones beyond the original shared-jurisdiction area; Kowloon routes Black Ledger operations through Forest corridors without joint arbitration.
Both cities acknowledge the Oath-Crossing as valid precedent while disputing each other's application of it.
The glade itself is maintained by a joint stewardship compact that has never lapsed, even during periods of active territorial dispute.

flags MIDGAARD
---
Midgaard's registry treats the Oath-Crossing as the foundational document for its northern territorial authority, establishing that Midgaard's charter system applies to contested zones through negotiated extension rather than conquest.
Midgaard's current application extends charter registration further into the Forest than the original terms specified.
The Continuity faction argues this extension is consistent with the spirit of the agreement: the Oath-Crossing committed both cities to resolving claims through Midgaard's charter system rather than force.
The Reckoning faction argues the extension violates the letter: the joint arbitration requirement was specific, and Midgaard's unilateral extension bypasses it.
Kowloon has filed formal objections three times; Midgaard has responded each time that the extension is charter-compliant and does not require joint arbitration.
Midgaard's position: the Oath-Crossing is a living document. Kowloon's position: it is a fixed commitment whose terms do not evolve unilaterally.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Black Ledger records the Oath-Crossing as the foundational covenant for northern route operations — the agreement making Great Northern Forest transit legally viable rather than perpetually contested.
Kowloon's current Forest operations include Black Ledger-classified activities that the joint arbitration requirement would technically require disclosing to Midgaard.
The Neon Covenant's position: classified crisis-protocol operations are exempt from the disclosure requirements, which were written for commercial territorial claims, not security operations.
Neither city has invoked the arbitration mechanism against the other; both are aware that doing so would require adjudicating each other's violations simultaneously.
Kowloon's internal assessment: the Oath-Crossing is holding. Neither city wants to replace it with something worse. The disputes are managed rather than resolved.
The glade's joint stewardship compact is one of the few active cooperation agreements between Midgaard and Kowloon that has never been challenged.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess views the Oath-Crossing as a partial success: two cities chose negotiation, established a documented joint process, and created a living governance framework for shared territory.
Partial because: the joint arbitration mechanism has never successfully been invoked, both cities have extended operations beyond the original terms, and the Forest's non-city inhabitants had no voice in the agreement.
Kiess's anti-secrecy doctrine requires disclosure of the Oath-Crossing's terms; both cities have disclosed the foundational terms but neither has disclosed its current interpretation.
Undisclosed interpretations of documented agreements are functionally equivalent to sealed warrants under Kiess's doctrine: the commitment exists but its application is hidden.
Kiess's frontier operations in the Northern Crown follow the joint arbitration requirement even where Midgaard and Kowloon do not, as a demonstration of the principle.
Kiess cannot compel Midgaard or Kowloon to include forest peoples in Forest governance but does include them in its own Northern Crown operations.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen holds the Oath-Crossing in civic memory primarily as a precedent for inter-city coexistence agreements rather than as a directly relevant governance document.
The Garden Ledger's analysis: the Oath-Crossing worked because both cities had more to gain from shared governance than from contested governance.
Rakuen's three annexation refusals from Midgaard are analyzed against the Oath-Crossing precedent: Midgaard offered absorption, not coexistence; the Oath-Crossing model would have been coexistence.
If Midgaard had offered Rakuen an Oath-Crossing equivalent — joint arbitration, mutual recognition, shared governance — Rakuen's response might have been different. Midgaard offered registry absorption instead. The Garden Ledger notes: absorption is not the same as recognition.
Both cities have honored Rakuen's coordinating requests under the Oath-Crossing's shared-jurisdiction framework during disaster-recovery operations, treating Rakuen as a de facto third party to the agreement — not documented in the Oath-Crossing itself, but established by practice.

