---
Rivennid in Kowloon maintain the most detailed cross-city network map of how the Oath-Crossing's terms are actually being applied versus formally stated.
Midgaard has extended charter registration into forty-three Forest locations not listed in the original Oath-Crossing joint zone; Kowloon has conducted Black Ledger operations through twelve Forest corridor segments without invoking joint arbitration.
Current finding: both cities are operating beyond the original terms in roughly equivalent scope, though in different functional domains — neither has exploited the Oath-Crossing more than the other.
The balance is not designed; it is the result of each city's independent pursuit of its interests encountering comparable constraints.
Rivennid in Kiess's disclosure advocacy network cite this finding as evidence the Oath-Crossing would benefit from formal review: the balance is accidental and could shift unpredictably.
Neither city's administration has synthesized the full cross-city view that Rivennid maintain as a network.
